flow_conditionals.content:
OVERVIEW:
Conditional statements execute code based on boolean conditions.
Use 'if-then-else' to control program flow.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  if condition then {
      // code when true
  } else if condition2 then {
      // code when condition2 is true
  } else {
      // code when all conditions are false
  }
</pre>

KEY POINTS:
• Condition must evaluate to a boolean (true/false)
• 'then' keyword is required after condition
• 'else if' allows multiple conditions
• 'else' clause is optional
• Braces { } define code blocks

EXAMPLE 1 - Simple If:
<pre>
  var age: int = 20;
  if age >= 18 then {
      print "You are an adult";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - If-Else:
<pre>
  var temperature: int = 25;
  if temperature > 30 then {
      print "It's hot outside";
  } else {
      print "Temperature is comfortable";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - Multiple Conditions:
<pre>
  var score: int = 85;
  if score >= 90 then {
      print "Grade: A";
  } else if score >= 80 then {
      print "Grade: B";
  } else if score >= 70 then {
      print "Grade: C";
  } else {
      print "Grade: F";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 4 - Complex Conditions:
<pre>
  var age: int = 25;
  var hasLicense: bool = true;
  if age >= 18 and hasLicense then {
      print "You can drive";
  } else if age >= 18 and not hasLicense then {
      print "Get a license first";
  } else {
      print "Too young to drive";
  }
</pre>

flow_loops.content:
OVERVIEW:
Loops execute code repeatedly based on conditions or iterations.
EBS supports while, for, foreach, and do-while loops.

WHILE LOOP:
Executes while condition is true. Condition checked before each iteration.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  while condition do {
      // code
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE - While Loop:
<pre>
  var count: int = 0;
  while count < 5 do {
      print "Count: " + count;
      count = count + 1;
  }
  // Output: Count: 0, Count: 1, Count: 2, Count: 3, Count: 4
</pre>

FOR LOOP:
Iterates over a range of values.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  for var i = start to end {
      // code
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE - For Loop:
<pre>
  for var i = 1 to 5 {
      print "Iteration: " + i;
  }
  // Output: Iteration: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5
</pre>

FOREACH LOOP:
Iterates over elements in an array or collection.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  foreach element in collection do {
      // code
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Foreach with Array:
<pre>
  var fruits: array[*] = ["apple", "banana", "orange"];
  foreach fruit in fruits do {
      print "Fruit: " + fruit;
  }
  // Output: Fruit: apple, Fruit: banana, Fruit: orange
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Foreach with JSON Array:
<pre>
  var numbers: json = [10, 20, 30, 40];
  var sum: int = 0;
  foreach num in numbers do {
      sum = sum + num;
  }
  print "Sum: " + sum;  // Output: Sum: 100
</pre>

DO-WHILE LOOP:
Executes at least once, then repeats while condition is true.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  do {
      // code
  } while condition;
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Do-While Loop:
<pre>
  var input: int = 0;
  do {
      print "Enter a positive number: ";
      input = 5;  // Simulated input
  } while input <= 0;
</pre>

NESTED LOOPS:
Loops can be nested for multi-dimensional iteration.

EXAMPLE - Nested For Loops:
<pre>
  for var row = 1 to 3 {
      for var col = 1 to 3 {
          print "[" + row + "," + col + "]";
      }
  }
</pre>

flow_break_continue.content:
OVERVIEW:
Loop control keywords alter normal loop execution flow.
• break (or exit) - Immediately exits the current loop
• continue - Skips remaining code and starts next iteration

BREAK STATEMENT:
Exits the loop entirely and continues with code after the loop.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  break;   // or exit;
</pre>

EXAMPLE 1 - Break in While Loop:
<pre>
  var i: int = 0;
  while i < 10 do {
      if i == 5 then {
          print "Breaking at: " + i;
          break;
      }
      print "i = " + i;
      i = i + 1;
  }
  print "Loop ended";
  // Output: i = 0, i = 1, i = 2, i = 3, i = 4, Breaking at: 5, Loop ended
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Break in Foreach:
<pre>
  var numbers: array[*] = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8];
  var found: bool = false;
  foreach num in numbers do {
      if num == 5 then {
          print "Found: " + num;
          found = true;
          break;
      }
  }
  // Stops iterating when 5 is found
</pre>

CONTINUE STATEMENT:
Skips the rest of the current iteration and proceeds to the next one.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  continue;
</pre>

EXAMPLE 1 - Continue in While Loop:
<pre>
  var i: int = 0;
  while i < 5 do {
      i = i + 1;
      if i == 3 then {
          continue;  // Skip printing when i is 3
      }
      print "Number: " + i;
  }
  // Output: Number: 1, Number: 2, Number: 4, Number: 5
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Continue to Skip Negatives:
<pre>
  var numbers: array[*] = [-2, 3, -1, 5, -4, 8];
  var sum: int = 0;
  foreach num in numbers do {
      if num < 0 then {
          continue;  // Skip negative numbers
      }
      sum = sum + num;
  }
  print "Sum of positives: " + sum;  // Output: Sum of positives: 16
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - Continue to Filter:
<pre>
  var items: array[*] = ["apple", "banana", "apricot", "orange", "avocado"];
  print "Items starting with 'a':";
  foreach item in items do {
      var firstChar: string = call str.substring(item, 0, 1);
      if firstChar != "a" then {
          continue;  // Skip items not starting with 'a'
      }
      print "  " + item;
  }
  // Output: apple, apricot, avocado
</pre>

USE CASES:
• break: Exit loop when target is found or condition met
• break: Prevent infinite loops with emergency exit
• continue: Skip invalid/unwanted items in iteration
• continue: Filter data during processing

flow_exceptions.content:
OVERVIEW:
Exception handling catches and manages runtime errors gracefully.
Use try-exceptions to prevent script crashes and handle errors.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  try {
      // code that might throw an exception
  } exceptions when exceptionVariable {
      // error handling code
      // exceptionVariable contains error message
  }
</pre>

KEY POINTS:
• Wrap risky code in try block
• exceptions keyword starts error handler
• when keyword binds exception to a variable
• Exception variable contains error details as string
• Code continues after exception handler
• Prevents script from crashing on errors

EXAMPLE 1 - File I/O Error Handling:
<pre>
  try {
      var content: string = call file.readTextFile("data.txt");
      print "File content: " + content;
  } exceptions when ex {
      print "Error reading file: " + ex;
      print "Using default data instead";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Division by Zero:
<pre>
  var numerator: double = 100.0;
  var denominator: double = 0.0;
  try {
      var result: double = numerator / denominator;
      print "Result: " + result;
  } exceptions when error {
      print "Cannot divide by zero: " + error;
      print "Using safe default value";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - Database Connection:
<pre>
  try {
      connect db = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb";
      use db {
          cursor c = select * from users;
          open c();
          while c.hasNext() do {
              var row = c.next();
              print row;
          }
          close c;
      }
      close connection db;
  } exceptions when dbError {
      print "Database error: " + dbError;
      print "Check connection settings";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 4 - JSON Parsing:
<pre>
  var jsonText: string = "{invalid json}";
  try {
      var data: json = call json.jsonFromString(jsonText);
      print "Parsed successfully";
  } exceptions when parseError {
      print "JSON parse error: " + parseError;
      // Use empty JSON object as fallback
      var data: json = call json.jsonFromString("{}");
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 5 - Multiple Operations:
<pre>
  var success: bool = false;
  try {
      // Multiple operations that might fail
      var exists: bool = call file.exists("config.json");
      if exists then {
          var config: string = call file.readTextFile("config.json");
          var settings: json = call json.jsonFromString(config);
          print "Configuration loaded";
          success = true;
      }
  } exceptions when ex {
      print "Failed to load config: " + ex;
      print "Using default settings";
  }

  if success then {
      print "Initialization complete";
  }
</pre>

COMMON USE CASES:
• File operations (read, write, delete)
• Database operations (connect, query)
• Network requests (HTTP, FTP)
• JSON parsing and manipulation
• Type conversions that may fail
• Array index access (out of bounds)
• Any builtin function that may fail

BEST PRACTICES:
• Always handle exceptions for I/O operations
• Provide meaningful error messages
• Include fallback behavior when possible
• Log errors for debugging
• Don't catch exceptions silently

